  "prompt": "What is the torque?",
  "response": "Torque is a measure of the force that can cause an object to rotate about an axis. It is the rotational equivalent of linear force. Torque depends on three main factors:\n\n1. **Magnitude of the Force**: The amount of force applied.\n2. **Direction of the Force**: The angle at which the force is applied relative to the lever arm.\n3. **Lever Arm (or Moment Arm)**: The perpendicular distance from the axis of rotation to the line of action of the force.\n\nThe formula for torque (\\( \\tau \\)) is:\n\n\\[\n\\tau = r \\times F \\times \\sin(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( r \\) = lever arm (distance from the axis to the point where the force is applied)\n- \\( F \\) = magnitude of the force\n- \\( \\theta \\) = angle between the force vector and the lever arm\n\nIf the force is applied perpendicular to the lever arm (\\( \\theta = 90^\\circ \\)), the torque is simply:\n\n\\[\n\\tau = r \\times F\n\\]\n\n### Units of Torque\nTorque is typically measured in:\n555- Newton-meters (N\u00b7m) in the SI system\n- Pound-feet (lb\u00b7ft) or pound-inches (lb\u00b7in) in the imperial system\n\n### Practical Applications\nTorque is essential in understanding rotational motion and is used in various applications, such as:\n- Tightening bolts or screws\n- Operating machinery\n- Analyzing the motion of wheels, gears, and engines\n- Designing mechanical systems like bicycles, cars, and robotics\n\nIn summary, torque describes how effectively a force causes an object to rotate. The greater the torque, the greater the rotational effect.",
